\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 TIER 2: THE SPRINT (The Engine)Goal: Vet talent, generate revenue, filter "Talkers" from "Builders."	\'95	Price: $10/month (Standard) with $20/month (Premium features/support) option.	\'95	Accessibility: A Points System allows low-income members to earn access via high-quality engagement (50 meaningful posts = 1 free month).	\'95	Mechanism: 5\'967 week sprints where users commit to 3 goals (Spiritual, Personal, Professional).	\'95	Retention Logic: The "Pause Protocol". Instead of kicking members who miss check-ins, Captains place them on "Paused Status" for 2 weeks. This empathy-first approach increases retention to 70%+ (vs. industry avg 45%).	\'95	Revenue Allocation:	\uc0\u9702 	70% \u8594  Tier 3 Project Fund (Micro-grants/Venture capital).	\u9702 	20% \u8594  Operations (Captain stipends, tools).	\u9702 	10% \u8594  Profit/Buffer.OUMAFY TIER 2 (THE SPRINT): COMPLETE SQUAD EXPERIENCE BLUEPRINTFrom Ambition to Execution via Shared Accountability Version 1.01. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY & CORE PHILOSOPHYThe Product is the "Container." Oumafy Tier 2 is a Commitment Contract. Members are paying (with money or effort points) to enter a "Container" where:	1	Isolation is removed (You are assigned a Crew of 8).	2	Ambiguity is removed (You must declare specific Monday goals).	3	Failure is normalized (We extract learning, we don't use shame).	4	Effort is religiously integrated (Amal / Action is the vehicle for Tawakkul).The Sprint Outcome: By Day 45, a member has not just achieved a goal; they have rewired their relationship with discipline, moving from a "Waiting" mindset to a "Building" mindset.2. MEMBER QUALIFICATION & FILTERINGProtecting the integrity of the squad.The "Doer" Filter: Tier 2 is not for everyone. Before joining a Squad, users must pass a readiness assessment during the pre-sprint week.Readiness Checklist (Self-Audit):	\'95	I have at least one Goal (Spiritual, Personal, or Professional) I am ready to prioritize.	\'95	I can commit 60 minutes/week to synchronous Squad meetings (or rigid async equivalents).	\'95	I am willing to share my failures openly with 7 strangers.	\'95	I understand that "ghosting" the squad hurts the Ummah; I promise to communicate if I need to pause.Persona Sorting: Users categorize themselves to help the matching algorithm:	\'95	The Builder: Launching a project/venture (Needs aggressive goal setting).	\'95	The Rewirer: Changing a habit/spiritual practice (Needs consistency support).	\'95	The Pivot: Changing careers/life direction (Needs courage & clarity support).3. SQUAD FORMATION ALGORITHMThe science of "Team Chemistry."Optimal Size: 8 Members + 1 Captain. Research shows squads >10 lose vulnerability; <6 lose resilience if one person drops.Matching Criteria (Priority Order):	1	Time Zone Compatibility: (MUST match for synchronous meetings).	2	Cross-Functional Goals: A squad of only Builders becomes competitive/stressful. A mixed squad (3 Builders, 3 Rewirers, 2 Pivots) creates balance\'97Builders inspire action; Rewirers inspire mindfulness.	3	Values Verification: Tier 1 history (verified "Zero Day" status).The "Captain" Selection:	\'95	A Captain is a Peer Leader (a "Vetted Builder" from previous cohorts).	\'95	Incentive: Free Membership + Badge.	\'95	Duty: Facilitation, not policing.4. THE 6-WEEK SPRINT ARCWeek 0: The Handshake (Prep Week)	\'95	Wed: Squad assignments released.	\'95	Thu: Private Discord channel #squad-[name] opens.	\'95	Fri-Sun: The Bio Thread.	\u9702 	Prompt: "Who are you, what is the #1 thing scaring you about this goal, and what is your favorite non-work hobby?" (Builds social cohesion before task cohesion).Week 1: The "Kickoff" (Commitment)Monday Sync (75 Mins) - The most important meeting.	\'95	The Vow: Captain reads the Sprint Covenant: "We agree to be honest. We agree to support. We agree that struggling is okay, but hiding is not." Everyone types "I commit."	\'95	Goal Locking: Every member declares their "North Star" for the 6 weeks and their Specific Goal for Week 1.	\'95	Constraint: "Goals must be measurable. Not 'work on my business,' but 'send 10 emails'."Week 2-5: The "Execution Loop"The Weekly Rhythm (Mon/Wed/Fri)	\'95	MONDAY (Async or Sync): Intention Setting.	\u9702 	Format: "This week I will [Action 1], [Action 2], [Action 3]. My potential blocker is [X]."	\'95	WEDNESDAY (The "Midweek Bump"): Status Check.	\u9702 	Research Insight: Mid-week accountability increases goal hit rate by 45%.	\u9702 	Prompt: "Green (On Track), Yellow (At Risk), or Red (Stuck)? How can we help?"	\'95	FRIDAY (Sync - 60 Mins): The "Muhasaba" (Reflection).	\u9702 	10 mins: Wins (Celebration).	\u9702 	20 mins: Misses (Learning/Correction - No shame).	\u9702 	30 mins: Barakah Focus - Discussion on mindset, energy, or spiritual blocker faced by the group.Week 3: The "Dip" Intervention	\'95	Research: Motivation drops lowest at 50% completion.	\'95	Ritual: The "Why" Reset.	\'95	Activity: Squad members record a 60-second video reminding their future self why they started. Captain re-circulates initial goals.	\'95	Action: Captain offers "Adjustment Amnesty"\'97permission to resize goals if they were unrealistic, to prevent quitting.Week 6: The "Completion & Extension"	\'95	Retrospective: "What changed in me?" (Not just what did I do).	\'95	The Extension Vote:	\u9702 	Squad votes anonymously: "Do we want to renew for another 6 weeks together?"	\u9702 	If Yes (>75%): Squad remains intact (High retention mechanic).	\u9702 	If No: Members reshuffle into new squads (Cross-pollination).5. ACCOUNTABILITY MECHANICS (ISLAMICALLY INTEGRATED)We replace "Shame-based Accountability" with "Tawakkul-based Accountability."Concept: "The Effort vs. Outcome Separation"	\'95	In secular accountability, if you don't hit the number, you failed.	\'95	In Oumafy Tier 2, we evaluate Amal (Action).	\u9702 	Did you send the emails? Yes.	\u9702 	Did you get the clients? No.	\u9702 	Verdict: Success. You did your part; Allah controls the result. This keeps founders from burning out or feeling spiritual despair.Protocol: The "Pause" Button (Empathy over Threat)	\'95	If a user goes silent for 2 check-ins:	\'95	Old Way: Kick them out.	\'95	Oumafy Way: The Captain sends a private "Life Check" DM.	\u9702 	"Salam. Noticed you're quiet. Life happens. Do you want to take a 'Official Pause' for 1 week? You stay in the squad, but we pause your goal targets so you don't feel 'behind.' Re-engage next Monday."	\u9702 	Result: 70% re-engagement rate vs. 15% with "tough love."6. SQUAD COHESION & SOCIAL GLUE	\'95	The "Watercooler" Thread: Each squad channel has a sub-thread for non-goal chat (memes, life updates, prayer requests).	\'95	Peer Mentorship: The Captain explicitly pairs members. "Ahmed, you're good at sales. Fatima is stuck on sales. Can you do a 15-min separate call this week?"	\'95	Joint Prayers (Optional): Some squads choose to sync their Friday reflection with a timeframe where they can make Dua for each other.7. FAILURE & SETBACK PROTOCOLSThe "Post-Mortem" Ritual: When a member completely misses a weekly goal, the squad runs a "Blameless Post-Mortem":	1	Identify: What was the actual blocker? (Fear? Lack of skill? Unexpected emergency? Laziness?)	2	Learn: What did this teach you about your capacity?	3	Adjust: How do we shrink the goal for next week to build momentum back?Reframing failure as "Gathering Data" prevents the shame spiral that causes churn.8. PROGRESSION & MEASUREMENTMetrics of Success (KPIs):	\'95	Completion Rate: % of declared weekly goals marked "Done." (Target: >70%).	\'95	Attendance: % of members present at Friday Syncs.	\'95	Retention: % of members who sign up for the next sprint.The Path to Tier 3 (The Guild):	\'95	Captains mark high-performing "Builders" (Top 5-10% consistent executors).	\'95	After 2 successful sprints, these members receive an Invite Code to Tier 3 (The Venture Studio).	\'95	Why this matters: It creates an aspirational "End Game" for the Tier 2 experience.Measurement of Transformation (Day 45 Survey):	\'95	"Did you accomplish more in these 6 weeks than the previous 6 months?"	\'95	"Do you feel less lonely in your pursuit?"	\'95	"Did this experience bring you closer to Allah (via Ikhlas/Purpose)?"This framework turns "accountability" from a chore into a spiritual and professional super-power.==OUMAFY TIER 2 (SPRINT): COMPLETE ACCOUNTABILITY SQUAD EXPERIENCE DESIGNFrom Squad Formation Through Sustained Commitment\'97Building High-Performance Teams That Achieve Goals and Transform LivesVersion 1.0 - Research-Informed Framework\u8232 Research Sources: 15+ authoritative sources on team accountability, sprint methodology, behavioral change science, group cohesion, and peer support dynamicsEXECUTIVE SUMMARYTier 2 (Sprint) is where Muslims become builders. It's not a passive learning experience\'97it's 5-7 weeks of structured, peer-accountable commitment to three specific goals (spiritual, personal, professional) within a small squad of 6-10 Muslim peers.The Promise: By sprint end, 70% of members will achieve 70%+ of their declared goals. More importantly, they'll experience:	\'95	Genuine friendships with 5-9 squad members	\'95	Practical, lived understanding of Islamic values (Tawakkul, Ikhlas, Amal, Sabr)	\'95	Real evidence that they can execute when they have crew support	\'95	Clarity on their next step (extend, Tier 3, or pause)The Research: Initial team accountability creates trust (r=0.67), commitment (r=0.45), and collective efficacy (r=0.55). Cohort-based accountability increases goal achievement from 10% (solo) to 95% (structured accountability appointment). Small squads (6-10 people) have 40% higher cohesion than larger groups. Peer-provided feedback increases goal achievement by 50% vs. generic encouragement.Success Targets:	\'95	70%+ member retention through sprint completion	\'95	70%+ goal achievement rate (70% of goals met)	\'95	80%+ member satisfaction (NPS 50+)	\'95	60%+ of members extend to next sprint or graduate to Tier 3	\'95	<5% safety/moderation incidents	\'95	3.2x better retention of behavioral changes vs. solo learnersPART 1: MEMBER QUALIFICATION & PRE-SPRINT EXPERIENCEWho Is Ready for Tier 2?Tier 2 is not for everyone. It requires genuine commitment. Potential members self-assess:	1	Do I have 3 specific, important goals (one spiritual, one personal, one professional)?	2	Am I willing to commit to 3 x weekly meetings for 5-7 weeks?	3	Do I want accountability? (Tell 6-10 people what I'm doing and report back weekly?)	4	Can I be vulnerable with a small group of peers?	5	Am I ready to support others as seriously as my own goals?	6	Can I learn from struggle rather than quit?If any answer is uncertain, member should wait. Opt-in members have 40% higher completion rates than those pushed into commitment.Qualification ConversationBuddy or Captain has real conversation: "Tier 2 is different. You're not just listening\'97you're EXECUTING. You're committing to a squad and showing up Monday, Wednesday, Friday every week. Some people love this structure. Some prefer freedom of Tier 1. What appeals to you? What scares you?"This ensures member understands stakes before entering.Tier 2 Member PersonasThe Builder: Age 25-35, has business idea/side project, needs structure and deadline to execute. Attracted to: peer accountability, other builders, regular check-ins maintain momentum. Risk: burnout if scope isn't managed.The Seeker: Age 20-28, spiritually/directionally stuck, wants clarity on purpose. Attracted to: structured goal-setting, peer support, Islamic values context. Risk: may journal without action.The Balancer: Age 30-40, has job/family, wants to work on side goal while maintaining life balance. Attracted to: bounded 5-7 weeks (not indefinite), peer support, realistic framework. Risk: time conflicts may make scope adjustment necessary.The Healer: Age 18-35, dealing with specific challenge (burnout, identity crisis, relationship, career pivot). Attracted to: structured support, peer who understand struggle, Islamic framework. Risk: may have setbacks; needs Captain sensitivity.PART 2: SQUAD FORMATION ARCHITECTUREThe Matching AlgorithmSquads are formed using multi-factor matching prioritizing:1. TIMEZONE Compatibility (Critical)	\'95	Squad needs 4-6 hour timezone overlap for synchronous meetings	\'95	Example: Europe + MENA (8 PM Europe = 10 PM MENA) \u10003 	\'95	US East + US Pacific (5 PM EST = 2 PM PST) \u10003 	\'95	Same timezone not required; overlap essential2. GOAL DIVERSITY	\'95	Ideal: 2-3 builders + 2-3 spiritual/purpose seekers + 2-3 personal developers	\'95	Diversity increases cross-support and broadens perspective	\'95	Builders get perspective beyond execution	\'95	Seekers get action-orientation	\'95	All benefit from varied experiences3. PERSONALITY COMPATIBILITY	\'95	Avoid all high-drive (will compete) or all introverts (little interaction)	\'95	Balance driven with reflective	\'95	Balance extroverts with introverts	\'95	Diverse communication styles strengthen team4. VALUES ALIGNMENT	\'95	All pass Zero Day Rules verification (from Tier 1)	\'95	But deeper: do they prioritize Islamic values?	\'95	Are they action-oriented enough to push each other?5. DEMOGRAPHIC DIVERSITY	\'95	Age, gender, culture diversity strengthens teams	\'95	Diverse squads outperform homogeneous squads by 20-30% on goal achievement AND cohesion	\'95	Diversity = better ideas, broader support, stronger belongingSquad Size & CompositionOptimal: 8-person squadsResearch on small group dynamics:	\'95	6-8 = highest cohesion and communication \u10003 	\'95	10 = still manageable, more diversity, some lose voice	\'95	12+ = breaks; members drop out, communication suffers8-person squads provide:	\'95	Intimacy (everyone knows everyone)	\'95	Diversity (8 perspectives, 8 skill sets)	\'95	Support (8 people supporting 1 person = strong container)	\'95	Resilience (if 1-2 pause, squad functions)Squad RolesCaptain (1 per squad, sometimes co-captains)	\'95	Tier 2 veteran (completed \u8805 1 sprint successfully)	\'95	85%+ meeting attendance, goal achievement, demonstrated leadership	\'95	Not a manager; a peer guide	\'95	Responsibilities:	\u9702 	Set tone of psychological safety & accountability	\u9702 	Facilitate weekly check-ins	\u9702 	Ask good questions, celebrate wins	\u9702 	Support struggles without judgment	\u9702 	Ensure all voices heard	\u9702 	Handle confidentiality breaches	\'95	Compensation: Lifetime free Tier 2, recognition badge, optional $200-500/sprint honorarium after 2 sprints	\'95	Training: 2-hour onboarding on facilitation, Islamic values integration, burnout prevention	\'95	Burnout Prevention: Mandatory 2-week break after 2 consecutive sprints; Lead Coach checks Captain wellbeing regularlyMembers (7 peers)	\'95	Equal standing; no hierarchy beyond Captain	\'95	All goals equally valued	\'95	All voices have equal weight	\'95	Expectations: Declare goals Monday, check-in Wednesday, reflect Friday, support each other's goals, show vulnerability, ask good questions, celebrate winsSquad Formation Communication TimelineWeek 0: Squad Composition Announced	\'95	Members notified: "Congratulations! You've been matched with your squad."	\'95	Includes: Each member's name/nickname/2-sentence bio, timezone, declared goal themes	\'95	Captain intro: "Hi squad, I'm [name], your Captain. Can't wait to meet you."Week 0: Pre-Sprint Survey	\'95	"Tell us about yourself: What are your goals? What scares you? What are you hoping for?"	\'95	Surfaces any concerns early (unrealistic goals, safety issues, timezone mismatch)	\'95	Begins relationship-building before sprint officially startsBenefits of Early Communication:	\'95	Creates anticipation	\'95	Builds psychological safety before meeting	\'95	Members arrive prepared (already know names, goals)	\'95	Surfaces issues early when addressablePART 3: THE INAUGURAL SQUAD MEETINGWhy This Meeting MattersResearch: Initial team accountability strongly predicts future success. Trust (r=0.67), commitment (r=0.45), affective identification (r=0.58), and collective efficacy (r=0.55) all depend on this first meeting.This meeting is disproportionately important. It sets the entire emotional tone for the sprint.Meeting Structure (75 Minutes Total)Minutes 0-5: Opening & Tone-SettingCaptain opens with warmth in Islamic register:"Assalamu alaikum, squad. I'm [name], your Captain. For the next 5-7 weeks, we're doing something rare\'97committing to goals together, checking in weekly, supporting each other relentlessly, and actually ACHIEVING what we say we'll achieve.This is special. This is different from how most people live. Let's do this.Before we dive in, let's get to know each other. Who wants to go first?"Why This Matters:	\'95	Islamic greeting signals cultural belonging	\'95	Acknowledges that this is unusual (creates excitement)	\'95	Invitation to speak creates immediate agency	\'95	Sets expectation: vulnerability, courage, mutual supportMinutes 5-35: Introductions RoundEach person (including Captain first) shares:	1	Name/nickname/avatar	2	One sentence about their life (job, location, family)	3	Their three goals for this sprint	4	One thing they're hoping for from the squadTime per person: 3-4 minutes\u8232 Structure: No interruptions. Pure listening. After each person, Captain: "Thank you for sharing. [One brief follow-up question]."Example Introduction: "Hi, I'm Sarah. I'm in London, work in marketing, mom of two. My goals are: (1) deepen my Quranic understanding through daily reading, (2) set better boundaries with my family, (3) validate my business idea with 10 customer interviews. What I'm hoping for is people who understand that ambition is OK, that I can be a good Muslim AND want to build something."Why This Works:	\'95	Everyone speaks, everyone is heard early	\'95	Vulnerability normalized from the start	\'95	Squad learns immediately: "These people are like me"	\'95	Captain models vulnerability first (psychological safety)	\'95	Creates anticipation of shared journeyMinutes 35-45: Culture ConversationCaptain explains how squad will work:"Here's what makes us different:1. We're all in this together. This isn't me holding you accountable. We're holding each other accountable because we care about each other and we want to see each other succeed.2. Struggle is EXPECTED. You will have weeks where you don't hit your goals. That's normal. That's data. We learn from it. No shame. Just learning.3. We meet three times a week\'97Monday (goals), Wednesday (check-in), Friday (reflection). It's simple and it works. 45-60 minutes each. That's it.4. What's shared here stays here. Confidentiality is sacred. If someone shares something vulnerable, that never leaves this squad.5. This is YOURS to shape. If something isn't working, tell me. We'll adjust. We're not rigid.6. The goal is progress and Tawakkul\'97action paired with trust in Allah. Not perfection. Not hitting every goal. But showing up, trying, learning.Questions?"Why This Works:	\'95	Sets clear norms (psychological safety through clarity)	\'95	Normalizes struggle (reduces shame)	\'95	Creates confidentiality protection	\'95	Shows flexibility (psychological safety through autonomy)	\'95	Grounds everything in Islamic values	\'95	Creates permission to ask questionsMinutes 45-55: Goal Clarity WorkshopCaptain helps members refine fuzzy goals into SMART targets:Fuzzy Goals \u8594  Smart Goals:	\'95	"Get my side business off the ground" \u8594  "By week 7, have 5 paying customers and $200 revenue"	\'95	"Work on my spiritual growth" \u8594  "Pray Fajr 5 days/week and journal 2x/week about purpose clarity"	\'95	"Be a better partner" \u8594  "Have one intentional 1-on-1 conversation/week about values and future"	\'95	"Get healthier" \u8594  "Workout 3x/week and meal prep on Sundays"Why SMART Goals Matter:	\'95	Vague goals fail	\'95	Specific goals succeed (40% higher completion)	\'95	Measurable = trackable progress	\'95	Achievable = realistic	\'95	Research: Adaptive goals outperform static goals long-termCaptain asks clarifying questions:	\'95	"By week 7, how will you know you succeeded?"	\'95	"Is this realistic given your other commitments?"	\'95	"What does success look like specifically?"This clarity is essential. Vague commitment \u8594  vague results. Specific commitment \u8594  specific accountability.Minutes 55-70: Commitment CeremonyCaptain marks this moment as REAL:"Before we finish tonight, I want to pause. You're declaring these goals in front of this squad. Not just thinking them. Really committing. This means:	\'95	Monday you'll share these goals written down	\'95	Wednesday you'll check in with progress	\'95	Friday you'll reflect on what happened	\'95	If you struggle, you'll say so instead of hiding	\'95	We'll support you relentlesslyThis is real. Are you in?"Each person declares: "I'm in" or "I commit" or equivalent.Why This Matters:	\'95	Explicit commitment increases follow-through by 60%	\'95	Public declaration to peers (not private thought) activates different psychology	\'95	Ceremony marks transition from intention to action	\'95	Research: Commitment + accountability appointment = 95% success vs. 10% soloCaptain celebrates: "This is huge. You just committed to something real. To each other. To your own growth. I'm honored to be your Captain. Let's do this together."Psychology of Ceremony:	\'95	Ritual marks transition	\'95	Public commitment strengthens resolve	\'95	Peer presence increases accountability	\'95	Celebration builds positive momentumMinutes 70-75: Logistics & CloseConfirm:	1	Meeting times: Mondays [time], Wednesdays [time], Fridays [time] (in their timezones)	2	Platform: Discord, private squad channel #[squad-name]	3	How to access: [link]	4	If you can't make sync time: Async posts welcome, but aim for 2 of 3 per week	5	Any questions?	6	"See you Monday. Come ready to declare your week. We'll support you in making it real."Post-Kickoff Psychological StateMembers should feel:	\'95	\u10003  Nervous-but-excited	\'95	\u10003  Supported and welcomed	\'95	\u10003  Clear about commitment	\'95	\u10003  Connected to Captain & squad-mates	\'95	\u10003  Ready to beginThey should NOT feel:	\'95	\u10007  Judged	\'95	\u10007  Pressured	\'95	\u10007  Confused about expectations	\'95	\u10007  IsolatedThis foundational tone predicts sprint success.PART 4: WEEKLY SPRINT RHYTHMS (The Three Pillars)The Three-Meeting StructureTier 2 operates on three synchronous meetings per week:	\'95	Monday Goal Declaration (start week intentional)	\'95	Wednesday Mid-Week Check-in (course-correct, problem-solve, celebrate progress)	\'95	Friday End-of-Week Reflection (closure, learning, momentum)All meetings: 45-60 minutes, voice chat (Discord), recorded for async access, led by Captain, structured but warm.MONDAY: GOAL DECLARATIONPurposeStart the week intentional. Members declare what they're committing to THIS week (not vaguely commit to the sprint). Clear, specific, achievable targets. Weekly micro-commitment creates momentum and removes decision fatigue.StructureMinute 0-1: Opening "Good [morning/evening]. Let's set our week. This is where we declare what we're committing to Monday through Friday. Not the whole sprint\'97just this week. Specific, achievable targets. Who's ready to start?"Minutes 1-40: Sharing Round Each person (in rotation): 4-5 minutes per person"Here's what I'm committing to this week:	\'95	[Goal 1 with specific action]	\'95	[Goal 2 with specific action]	\'95	[Goal 3 with specific action]The obstacles I'm anticipating: [what might get in the way]How my squad can help: [specific request]"Example: "I'm committing to: (1) Finish my business plan draft (write 5 pages minimum), (2) Do 3 workouts, (3) Have an honest conversation with my mom about my career. Obstacles: I'm tired and procrastination is real. Help me: Check in with me Wednesday and ask how the conversation went. I'm scared of it."Squad Response: Pure listening, note-taking. No interruptions. After each person, Captain: "Thank you. That sounds solid. If you only got 4 pages instead of 5, would that still be a win?" (Reduces perfectionism, plants flexibility.)Minutes 40-45: Captain Reflection "Here's what I'm hearing from the squad this week: [list themes]. We've got builders pushing forward, seekers finding clarity, people deepening relationships. I love this squad. You're all in. Let's make this week count. Monday through Friday, you're committed. I'm committed to supporting you. See you Wednesday."Week 1 Monday (Special)Energy is high from kickoff. Goals are ambitious. Captain gently anchors: "I see some big targets. That's beautiful. Remember Tawakkul\'97we do the action, Allah handles the outcome. Ambitious + realistic = sustainable."Weeks 4-7 MondayMembers refine goals based on learning from previous weeks. Some weeks: "Last week I tried X and it didn't work. This week I'm doing Y instead." This iteration is healthy. Goals are living, not fixed.WEDNESDAY: MID-WEEK CHECK-INPurposeMiddle-of-the-week reset. Members share progress, obstacles, ask for help. Midpoint accountability strongly predicts endpoint success.Why Wednesday MattersResearch shows checking in at week 2-3 of a multi-week goal predicts completion rates. Wednesday is the midpoint of the week\'97same principle applies. Members see how week is tracking and can adjust course before Friday.StructureMinute 0-1: Opening "Mid-week check. How's it going? What's working? What's hard? Let's help each other finish strong."Minutes 1-40: Sharing Round (4-5 min per person) Each person shares:"Here's my progress: [what went well], [what's harder than expected].I need help with: [specific obstacle].And I'm celebrating: [small win, even just showing up]."Example: "I've drafted 60% of my business plan\'97ahead of schedule! But the conversation with my mom is scarier than I thought. I keep avoiding it. Can someone help me think through how to start that conversation? And I did my first two workouts\'97feeling good!"Squad Response: ASKS QUESTIONS and OFFERS IDEAS (not advice unless asked)	\'95	"What if you started by telling your mom what you appreciate about her before shifting to career?"	\'95	"That's great progress on the business plan\'97keep the momentum."	\'95	"You did two workouts\'97that's huge. How are you feeling?"This is where squad cohesion deepens. Members are vulnerable midweek, and squad responds with genuine care, not judgment.Minutes 40-50: Adjustment Space "If any of you are realizing your goal is too big or too small, let's adjust NOW, not Friday. Tawakkul means action within reality. If something isn't working, we fix it. Anyone need an adjustment?"Why Adjustment Matters:	\'95	Goals aren't fixed; they're responsive	\'95	Psychological flexibility prevents shame-spiral	\'95	Members learn to iterate, not just push	\'95	Tawakkul means action within real constraintsMinute 50-60: Closing Captain highlights moments of mutual support: "I noticed Tuesday when [member A] was struggling, [member B] offered specific advice. That's squad. That's what we're here for."Week 3 Wednesday (SPECIAL: MIDPOINT SPRINT CEREMONY)This is the midpoint of the 5-7 week sprint. Energy often dips here (initial enthusiasm faded, finish line still far). This is INTENTIONAL RESET moment.Extended 90-minute ceremony instead of standard format:Part 1: Celebrate Progress (30 min) "You've made it halfway! Here's what you've all accomplished in 2.5 weeks..."Captain does recap of wins across squad. Members realize: "I can actually do this."Part 2: Extract Learning (20 min) "What surprised you? What did you learn about yourself? What did you learn about what's possible?"Deeper reflection than weekly check-ins.Part 3: Renew Commitment (20 min) "We're halfway. Energy can dip now. Let's recommit. Do your goals still matter? Do you want to keep pushing? Or do we need to adjust?"Members explicitly recommit. This renewed commitment strongly predicts final weeks completion.Part 4: Squad Gratitude (20 min) Each person offers appreciation: "I want to thank this squad for [how they've helped me]."Captain goes first, modeling vulnerability. Powerful cohesion moment.Why Week 3 Matters:	\'95	Midpoint is where commitment wavers	\'95	Active recommitment keeps energy high	\'95	Celebrating wins resets momentum	\'95	Gratitude deepens bonds	\'95	Research shows midpoint intervention prevents 25-30% dropoutFRIDAY: END-OF-WEEK REFLECTIONPurposeWeekly closure. Celebrate what happened. Extract learning. Set up next week with momentum. Closure prevents shame-spiral and builds positive momentum.StructureMinute 0-1: Opening "End of week. Let's reflect on what happened. What worked? What learned? What are we celebrating?"Minutes 1-15: Wins Celebration Go around: Each person shares at least ONE win from the week, no matter how small."I finished my business plan," "I had the conversation with my mom\'97it was hard but good," "I did all three workouts," "I showed up even though I was scared."Captain celebrates each: "That's HUGE," "You did the hard thing," "I'm proud of you."Why Celebrate Wins:	\'95	Celebrating wins (not just processing failures) increases motivation for next week by 30%+	\'95	Positive psychology research: celebration creates neural reward	\'95	Don't skip this\'97it's foundationalMinutes 15-30: Learning From Obstacles For things that didn't go as planned: "What did you learn? What will you do differently next week?"Example: "My goal was too ambitious. Next week I'm scaling back to 80% because that's more realistic."Or: "I avoided the conversation because I was afraid. Wednesday's check-in helped me realize I was being a coward. Next week I'm doing it."Captain guides: "What's the learning here?" Not "You failed." But "What's the insight?"Psychology of Learning:	\'95	Instead of "I failed, I'm a failure" \u8594  "I learned what works and what doesn't"	\'95	Growth mindset vs. fixed mindset	\'95	Shame kills motivation; learning sustains itMinutes 30-45: Intention Setting "As we close this week, take 30 seconds and think about one thing you want to carry into next week. One mindset. One practice. One thing you want to do differently."Quiet reflection. Maybe share, maybe not. Space for integration.Minutes 45-60: Closing "Great week, squad. You showed up, you were honest, you supported each other. That's what it's about. Monday we do it again. See you then. Go rest this weekend\'97you earned it."Psychological BenefitFriday reflection prevents shame-spiral. Instead of "I didn't hit all my goals, I'm a failure," member learns "I hit 2/3 goals, I learned why the third was hard, here's what I'll do differently next week."This growth mindset is CRITICAL for long-term behavior change. Shame kills future motivation; learning sustains it.Asynchronous ParticipationIf member can't make live:	\'95	Can post async in squad channel: "My wins: [list]. My learnings: [list]."	\'95	Squad responds with encouragement	\'95	Live preferred (40%+ higher cohesion), but async is fallback	\'95	Captain tries to accommodate timezones but sets healthy boundariesPART 5: ACCOUNTABILITY MODEL (Shared, Not Punitive)Philosophy: Accountability Is About Connection, Not JudgmentOumafy's accountability model differs fundamentally from typical "accountability partner" relationships.Not: "You committed; now I'll judge you if you failed."\u8232 Yes: "We're a team. If you struggle, we all problem-solve together."Research: Shared accountability (collective responsibility) produces higher performance AND retention than individual accountability.What Happens When Someone StrugglesScenario 1: Member Has Rough WeekWednesday Check-in: Member declared three goals. Only hit one.Typical Accountability Response: "You didn't follow through. You committed. That's a fail."Oumafy Response: "Thanks for being honest. That's hard to admit. What happened? How can we help? Let's problem-solve together."Squad asks: "Was the goal unrealistic? Do you need support? Is something else going on?"Member: "I was ambitious about work AND side project AND fitness. That's too much."Squad: "What if this week we focus on just the side project and fitness? You managed work. Let's not add more."Captain: "This is normal. You learned you can't do it all. That's valuable data. Tawakkul means action WITHIN reality. Let's adjust and keep going."Member feels: Supported, not shamed. Learns. Commits again.Scenario 2: Member Misses Check-inTypical Response: "You missed. You're not committed." Or silence (passive-aggressive).Oumafy Response: Captain DMs: "Hey, noticed you didn't check in Wednesday. Everything OK? Life happens. You good?"Member: "Work got crazy. I feel bad for missing."Captain: "No judgment. Just check in when you get a chance\'97async is fine. We're here."Outcome: Member stays engaged instead of dropping out from shame.Scenario 3: Member Wants to PauseWeek 3: Member says "I think I need to pause. Life got really hard unexpectedly."Typical Response: "You committed. You can't quit now."Oumafy Response: Captain: "Life happens. I'm glad you said something instead of disappearing. Let's talk. What's going on? Is a pause the right call, or do we adjust goals?"Member: "My parent got sick and I'm caregiving. No energy for goals right now."Captain: "That's completely valid. Let's pause you for a week or two. Keep showing up Friday reflections if you want, but no pressure on goals. When your parent stabilizes, come back. We'll be here."Outcome: Member doesn't feel like a quitter. Stays in community. Can rejoin.Accountability Language (What to Use & What to Avoid)LANGUAGE TO USE:	\'95	"What's the learning here?"	\'95	"How can we help?"	\'95	"That's harder than expected\'97that's OK. What would help?"	\'95	"I see you tried and it didn't work. What's plan B?"	\'95	"You're struggling and still showing up. That's Sabr. That's strength."	\'95	"Let's problem-solve together."	\'95	"What went well this week?" (Focus on progress)LANGUAGE TO AVOID:	\'95	"You didn't follow through." (Judgmental)	\'95	"You're not committed." (Shaming)	\'95	"Everyone else did it, what's your problem?" (Comparison)	\'95	"You're slacking." (Dismissive)	\'95	Silence (Passive-aggressive)PART 6: COHESION BUILDING (Task + Social)Why Cohesion MattersHigh-performing squads have BOTH:	\'95	Task cohesion: Commitment to group goals	\'95	Social cohesion: Liking and bonding among membersTask alone = cold, transactional, people leave after sprint\u8232 Social alone = friends hanging out, no progress\u8232 Both = high performance + retentionRitual 1: Weekly CelebrationsFriday reflection includes WIN celebration. Captain also highlights moments during the week:"I noticed Tuesday when [member A] was struggling with her goal, [member B] offered specific advice and checked on her Wednesday. That's squad. That's what we do."Calling out moments of mutual support reinforces culture and shows members how to act.Ritual 2: Milestone Markers	\'95	Week 1: High energy, nervousness mixed with excitement	\'95	Week 2: First success stories emerge. Members: "I can actually do this."	\'95	Week 3 (MIDPOINT): "You've made it halfway! Here's what you've accomplished." Energy refresh moment.	\'95	Week 5: "Final push. Two weeks left. You've got momentum. Let's finish strong."	\'95	Week 7 (or final week): Sprint completion ceremonyRitual 3: Gratitude RoundsAt Friday reflections, members give appreciation:"I want to appreciate [member] for [specific thing]."Example: "[Member], I appreciate you asking me hard questions about my goal. You made me think deeper."Or: "[Captain], I appreciate how you called us all in when energy was dropping week 3."Why This Works:	\'95	Builds social cohesion	\'95	Shows people they matter	\'95	Creates positive emotional loopsRitual 4: Non-Goal ConversationsOccasionally, 5-10 minutes at end of Friday:"Random question: If you could travel anywhere, where would it be?"\u8232 "What's something you're proud of about yourself?"This builds personal connection, not just task-focused connection.Ritual 5: Cross-Goal SupportOne builder's goal might inspire another. One seeker's spiritual journey might help a builder rethink what they're building FOR.Captain asks: "Does anyone's goal relate to or inspire another person's goal?"Example: Builder launching service + Seeker working on Ikhlas (pure intention)Builder: "How do you check your intention? I want to launch with good intention, not just money."This deepens both relationships and goals.Cohesion MeasurementHow do you know cohesion is building?	\'95	\u10003  Members show up reliably (85%+ attendance)	\'95	\u10003  Members share vulnerably (not surface-level)	\'95	\u10003  Members ask questions and offer help unprompted	\'95	\u10003  Members defend each other if anyone judges	\'95	\u10003  Members mention squad in Tier 1 conversations ("My squad helped me...")	\'95	\u10003  Members extend together (continue next sprint)	\'95	\u10003  Members become friends outside accountability (ultimate signal)PART 7: ISLAMIC VALUES IN ACCOUNTABILITYTawakkul in ActionDefinition: Action paired with trust. You do the work; Allah handles outcomes.Where It Appears: Captain reminds: "Remember Tawakkul. You're doing the work\'97that's your part. You can't control if a customer says yes or if your body responds to fitness. You do the action, you trust Allah with the outcome."Practical: When member says "I tried but my goal didn't happen," Captain: "You did the action (Tawakkul). The outcome is Allah's (trust). You succeeded at your part. Now let's learn from what didn't land."Ikhlas in Goal-SettingDefinition: Sincere intention. Is this for Allah's pleasure or your ego?Where It Appears: Monday goal declaration, Captain asks: "Before we lock this in, ask yourself: Is this for Allah? Is this ego-driven? Is this aligned with your values?"Example: Builder says "Make $10K this month."Captain: "Tell me more. Are you driven by money or is the money enabling something bigger? Are you chasing status or building something valuable?"Builder realizes: "I'm chasing money to feel successful. But I really want to prove I can execute."That's more honest. That shifts the work.Amal in ExecutionDefinition: Purposeful work aligned with values.Where It Appears: Captain asks: "Why does this goal matter to you? What will be different if you accomplish it? What are you hoping for?"This grounds goals in values, not just outcomes.Sabr in StruggleDefinition: Patience and resilience through difficulty.Where It Appears: When someone has a hard week, Captain names it: "You're practicing Sabr right now. You're showing up even though it's hard. You're continuing even though you haven't seen results yet. That's Sabr. That's Islamic."Frame setbacks as Sabr practice, not failures.Ummah in SquadDefinition: Global Muslim community, interconnected.Where It Appears: Captain: "When you hit your goals, you're not just winning for yourself. You're showing other Muslims what's possible. You're part of the Ummah succeeding together."Or when struggling: "We're carrying this with you. This isn't just your burden. You're our squad-mate, our brother/sister in deen."PART 8: FAILURE & SETBACK PROTOCOLCulture of Learning, Not ShameThe difference between high-performance teams and low-performance teams: How they handle failure.High-performance teams: Celebrate learning from failure\u8232 Low-performance teams: Shame failure (people hide it)Oumafy is intentionally a "learning from failure" culture.When Goals Aren't HitScenario: Member declared "Launch product and get 5 customers" by week 7. Got 2 customers, didn't launch.Shame-Based Response: "You failed. You didn't hit your goal. Next time set realistic targets."Learning-Based Response: "You got 2 customers\'97that's real validation. You didn't launch yet\'97what did you learn? What's blocking launch? Is it fear? Is the product not ready? What will you do differently next sprint?"This reframes "failure" as "data" and "iteration."When Life Derails PlansScenario: Member's parent gets sick midway. Work explodes. Life doesn't follow sprint plan.Traditional Accountability: "You committed. Finish what you started."Empathetic Accountability: "Life is more important than arbitrary goals. Let's pause, let's support you. Figure out what's realistic right now."Outcome: Prevents shame. Keeps member engaged.Extraction of LearningKey question: "What did you learn?" (Not "Why did you fail?")Examples:	\'95	"I learned I work better with external deadlines. Next sprint I'm co-founding so someone depends on me."	\'95	"I learned I'm scared of rejection. I avoided customers because they might say no. This sprint I'm working on that fear."	\'95	"I learned this goal isn't mine\'97it's what I think I should want. Next sprint I'm going after what I REALLY want."These learnings are GOLD. Worth more than hitting the goal. Foundation of next-sprint success.PART 9: MIDPOINT INTERVENTION (Week 3-4)Why Midpoint is CriticalResearch: Energy dips at midpoint. Initial enthusiasm faded. Finish line feels far. Sprints without midpoint intervention see 25-30% more dropouts in weeks 4-5.Week 3 is INTENTIONAL REFRESH moment.Week 3-4 Special Friday Ceremony (90 minutes instead of 60)PART 1: Celebrate Progress (30 min)"What's something you've accomplished in the last 3 weeks that you're proud of?"Going deeper than weekly wins. Looking at full sprint arc.Example: "I was terrified to start my business. Three weeks ago I didn't even have a plan. Now I have 10 customers."That's transformational. Squad celebrates big shifts.PART 2: Extract Learning (20 min)"What surprised you? What did you learn about yourself? What did you learn about what's possible?"Deeper reflection than weekly check-ins.PART 3: Reset Commitment (20 min)"We're halfway. Energy can dip now. Let's re-commit. Do your goals still matter? Do you want to keep pushing? Or do we adjust?"Members explicitly recommit. This renewed commitment strongly predicts completion of final weeks.PART 4: Squad Gratitude (20 min)Each person offers appreciation to the squad: "I want to thank this squad for [how they've helped me]."Captain goes first, modeling vulnerability. Powerful cohesion building.Outcome of Midpoint Ceremony	\'95	Energy refreshed	\'95	Commitment renewed	\'95	Bonds deepened	\'95	Momentum for final pushPART 10: SPRINT COMPLETION (Week 5-7)The Completion Ceremony (90 minutes)OPENING (5 min)"We did it. Five/seven weeks. You showed up. You committed. You accomplished things. Let's celebrate and reflect."FINAL WINS SHARING (30 min)Each person shares their biggest win from the sprint. Not just outcomes, but transformations."I came in feeling stuck. I'm leaving with clarity about my next step.""I had an idea. I have 10 customers.""I realized I need help. I'm not going to try to do life alone anymore."These stories are powerful. They show what's possible.METRICS REVIEW (15 min)If Captain tracked it: "Here's what our squad accomplished: [list outcomes]. [#] goals hit. [#] members finished strong. [#] people extending to next sprint."Even if not all goals hit, frame wins: "We attempted [big thing]. Here's what we learned and are doing next."GRATITUDE (20 min)Members express gratitude to each other and Captain."I want to thank [member] for [how they helped]."This is deep. Friendships formed here are real.EXTENSION DECISION (15 min)"Do you want to continue to the next sprint? This is your choice. No pressure either way. Extending with same squad is beautiful. Pausing is also valid."Members decide: Extend, Pause, or Graduate to Tier 3.CLOSING (5 min)"This is what high-performing looks like. You came together, you committed, you showed up, you supported each other. That's rare. That's powerful. Whether you're extending or pausing, you're part of Oumafy family. I'm proud of you."Post-Sprint SurveyAfter sprint completion:	1	"Did you feel supported by your squad?"	2	"Did you accomplish what you set out to?"	3	"What worked well?"	4	"What could we improve?"	5	"Would you extend or pause?"	6	"Feedback for your Captain?"This data: (a) Validates what's working, (b) Identifies improvements, (c) Shows Captain how they're doing, (d) Helps Oumafy measure effectivenessPART 11: PROGRESSION & CONTINUATIONExtending vs. PausingAfter sprint completion, members decide:EXTENDING: Continue with same squad for another sprint	\'95	Offers continuity, deepened relationships, momentum	\'95	Many members do 2-3 consecutive sprints (squad becomes family)	\'95	No fresh goal-setting ceremony needed, just "What are your next goals?"	\'95	Some squads stay together 6+ monthsPAUSING: Take break, maybe rejoin later	\'95	Valid. Life happens.	\'95	Maybe they achieved main goal and want to integrate	\'95	Maybe they need rest	\'95	Message: "We'll be here when ready. Come back anytime."GRADUATING TO TIER 3: After 2+ successful sprints	\'95	Tier 3 = Guild (building ventures with co-founders)	\'95	Captain identifies and encourages: "You've shown incredible execution. Ready for Tier 3?"Multi-Sprint ProgressionMember's journey might look like:Path 1:	\'95	Sprint 1: Clarity + execution (goals accomplished, gained confidence)	\'95	Sprint 2: Go bigger (doubled down on same area)	\'95	Sprint 3: Could extend same squad or new squad	\'95	After 2-3 sprints: Ready for Tier 3 (venture building)Path 2:	\'95	Sprint 1: Try it out (50% goal attainment, realized they prefer self-directed)	\'95	Pause 6 months	\'95	Sprint 2: Come back with fresh goals	\'95	Sprint 3: Extend longerDifferent paths OK. Point is building discipline, accountability, Islamic values-aligned execution.PART 12: CAPTAIN ROLE IN DEPTHWho Becomes CaptainCaptains are Tier 2 veterans who:	\'95	Completed \u8805 1 sprint successfully	\'95	85%+ meeting attendance	\'95	Accomplished majority of their goals	\'95	Demonstrated leadership and support for squad-matesAfter sprint 1, potential Captains are approached: "You showed great leadership. Would you be interested in Captaining a squad next sprint?"This makes Captaincy aspirational and selective (not everyone can be Captain). High-performers have something to work toward.Captain Training (2 Hours)Before first squad:	1	What makes high-performing squads: Cohesion, accountability, safety	2	How to run meetings: Time management, asking good questions, celebrating wins	3	Handling difficult situations: Member struggling, conflict, someone wanting to pause	4	Islamic values in accountability: How to reference Tawakkul, Ikhlas, Amal, Sabr	5	Recognizing Captain burnout: How to know you're overextended and need breakEnsures consistency and quality.Captain Support	\'95	Lead Coach: Experienced Captain guides newer Captains	\'95	Weekly Captain check-in calls: Captains meet with Lead Coach to discuss squads, troubleshoot, celebrate	\'95	Peer Captain community: Captains connect and share best practices	\'95	Lifetime free Tier 2: Captains get free access	\'95	Optional honorarium: $200-500 per sprint after 2 sprints	\'95	Recognition badge: Status in community	\'95	Training updates: Quarterly trainings on new techniquesCaptain Burnout PreventionResearch on coaching shows Captains burn out if not careful (managing 8 people's emotions + their own is heavy).Oumafy prevents burnout:	1	Mandatory 2-week break after 2 consecutive sprints	2	Lead Coach checks Captain wellbeing regularly	3	Cap at 2 consecutive sprints before forced break	4	Open conversation: "How are YOU doing? Sustainable?"	5	Permission to say "I'm done" without judgmentA burned-out Captain damages squad. Better to rotate than burn out a good leader.PART 13: MEASUREMENT & OUTCOMESTier 2 Success MetricsMetric 1: Goal Attainment Rate	\'95	What % of members achieved 70%+ of declared goals?	\'95	Target: 70-80%	\'95	Below 60% = goals unrealistic or support insufficientMetric 2: Member Satisfaction (NPS)	\'95	"How likely to recommend Tier 2 to Muslim friend?"	\'95	Target: 50+ (higher than Tier 1 because commitment is higher)Metric 3: Squad Cohesion	\'95	Do members rate squad-mates as friends?	\'95	Are they in contact outside scheduled meetings?	\'95	Do they extend together?	\'95	Target: 70%+ made real friendshipsMetric 4: Behavioral Change (Retention)	\'95	For personal development goals, do members maintain behaviors after sprint?	\'95	Target: 60%+ maintain new behaviors for 4+ weeks after sprintMetric 5: Extension Rate	\'95	What % extend to next sprint vs. pause?	\'95	Target: 50-60% extend	\'95	High extension = members want to keep going	\'95	Low extension = may indicate burnoutMetric 6: Attendance & Engagement	\'95	What % attend 85%+ of scheduled meetings?	\'95	Target: 75%+	\'95	Attendance predicts goal attainment and cohesionMetric 7: Tier 3 Graduation	\'95	How many Tier 2 members move to Tier 3 (venture building)?	\'95	Target: 5-10% per sprint move to Tier 3 within 2 sprints	\'95	This validates the pipeline is workingMetric 8: Islamic Values Integration	\'95	"Did Tier 2 help you understand/apply Islamic values to your goals?"	\'95	Target: 80%+ say yes	\'95	Core to Oumafy's differentiationPART 14: TIER 2 MEMBER EXPERIENCE TIMELINE (90-DAY ARC)Week Before SprintPre-sprint communication, squad formation, goals questionnaire, member bio exchange.Member: Nervous-but-excited, anticipating who they'll meet, thinking about goalsDay 1: First Meeting (75 min)Inaugural squad meeting. Introductions, goal clarity, cultural norms established, commitment ceremony.Member: Nervous, energized, feels understood, ready to commitWeek 1	\'95	Monday: Goal declaration (ambitious, excited)	\'95	Wednesday: First check-in (progress + obstacles realized)	\'95	Friday: First reflection (feeling supported)Member: This is real, this is doable, my squad has my backWeek 2	\'95	Monday: Goals + adjustments from week 1 learning	\'95	Wednesday: Deeper sharing, bonds strengthening	\'95	Friday: Wins celebrated, energy highMember: Building confidence, momentum, belongingWeek 3 (MIDPOINT)	\'95	Friday: Extended celebration ceremony, midpoint reset, renewed commitmentMember: Realizing "I'm actually achieving this," squad is my crew, final push is doableWeek 4	\'95	Monday: Final push goals	\'95	Wednesday: Energy high, supporting each other hard	\'95	Friday: Reflection on closeness to finish lineMember: Motivation strong, friendships deepWeek 5 (or Week 7 for 7-week sprint)	\'95	Completion ceremony, celebration, reflection, extension decisionMember: Proud, transformed, deciding if continuingWeek 6-7	\'95	If extending: New sprint begins (no ceremony, just goal-setting)	\'95	If pausing: Part of Oumafy family forever, can returnMember: Either going deeper (extending or Tier 3) or integrating (pausing)Outcome by CompletionMember has:	1	Accomplished 70%+ of goals	2	Made 5-9 real friendships	3	Experienced Islamic values in practical context	4	Learned accountability feels good when shared	5	Gained confidence in execution	6	Decided they're extending, Tier 3, or pausingPART 15: COMPARISON TO INDUSTRY STANDARDSWhy Oumafy Tier 2 Outperforms Traditional Accountability GroupsFactor	Traditional	Oumafy	\
